Chapter One: Project planning
1.1 Introduction

In Ethiopia, accessing appropriate healthcare remains a significant challenge for many patients due to fragmented information, lack of transparency in hospital services, and unequal distribution of medical facilities across regions. Patients often visit multiple hospitals before finding one that can properly address their medical condition, accept their budget, or is conveniently located. This trial-and-error approach leads to delayed treatment, increased healthcare costs, and in severe cases, deterioration of health conditions.
The problem is further compounded by the absence of a centralized, accessible system that provides reliable information about hospital capabilities, service availability, and cost structures. While some hospitals maintain individual websites or social media pages, there is no unified platform that allows patients to compare options based on their specific needs.
CareConnect is proposed as a solution to this problem. It is a digital health platform designed to intelligently connect patients with the most suitable hospitals based on symptoms, financial capacity, geographic location, and service requirements. The system will be available via mobile and web applications, with offline supported features to ensure accessibility for users in low connectivity rural areas.
This document serves as the Software Project Management plan for the development of CareConnect. It outlines the feasibility, scope, schedule, cost, resources, risk analysis, and change control strategies that will guide the project from initiation to closure. The plan follows established software project management principles and is aligned with Ethiopian healthcare digitalization initiatives.
1.2 Feasibility Study

Technical Feasibility
CareConnect can be developed using existing mobile and web technologies. Integration with hospital databases is achievable through APIs, while offline functionality can be supported using local storage and synchronization methods. Security requirements such as encryption and authentication are technically feasible with current standards.
Economic Feasibility
The project requires initial investment in development, training, and infrastructure. However, long‑term benefits include reduced patient misdirection, improved hospital efficiency, and potential cost savings for both patients and healthcare providers. Funding opportunities may be available through the Ministry of Health, NGOs, and private sponsors.
Operational Feasibility
Hospitals and patients are expected to benefit from improved transparency and accessibility. Training programs for hospital staff will support adoption, while the system’s user‑friendly design ensures ease of use for patients. The operational environment is supportive of such a system, given Ethiopia’s growing digital health initiatives.
Legal and Regulatory Feasibility
The project must comply with Ethiopian health data privacy laws specifically aligning with the Ethiopian Data Protection Proclamation No. 1321/2024 (if effective) and relevant Ministry of Health digital health directives and obtain approval from the Ministry of Health. Implementing strong data protection measures, including encryption and secure authentication, will ensure compliance and reduce risks associated with patient data handling.
Schedule Feasibility
The project can be implemented in phases:
▪Short‑term: Pilot rollout in Addis Ababa.
▪Medium‑term: Expansion to Oromia and other regions.
▪Long‑term: Nation wide deployment.
The core system development (design, coding, testing) is estimated at 18 weeks.

