3.4.3 Lessons Learned (Literature Review)

This subsection reviews existing literature and comparable systems to inform the design and management of CareConnect.

Key Lessons from Ethiopian Healthcare IT Studies
	Fragmented information systems are the norm – Many Ethiopian hospitals use standalone, paper‑based or incompatible digital systems. A 2021 Ministry of Health assessment found that less than 30% of public hospitals had interoperable patient records. Lesson: CareConnect must not rely on real‑time integration with legacy hospital systems; instead, it should operate as an independent directory with manual data updates by hospital staff.
	Offline capability is essential for rural areas – Research from the Ethiopian Public Health Institute indicates that only 15% of rural health facilities have reliable internet. Lesson: Offline‑first design (local SQLite storage with periodic sync) is not optional – it is a core requirement.
	Cost transparency reduces patient delays – A study published in the Ethiopian Journal of Health Development (2022) found that 68% of patients reported unexpected costs as a reason for delaying or avoiding care. Lesson: Displaying estimated costs before admission, as required in FR‑03, directly addresses this barrier.

	User acceptance depends on simplicity – Usability testing of a similar health matching prototype in Addis Ababa (2023) showed that users abandoned the app if symptom input required more than three fields. Lesson: CareConnect limits symptom input to a simple text field with auto‑suggest, as seen in Figure 5.2.
	Change management is critical – A review of failed health IT projects in low‑resource settings (WHO, 2020) identified insufficient stakeholder involvement as a primary cause. Lesson: The project established a Change Control Board (Section 1.8) and engaged pilot hospitals from Week 3 to validate requirements.

