Chapter Seven: Conclusion and Recommendations

7.1 Conclusion

The CareConnect project has successfully developed a comprehensive Software Project Management (SPM) plan for a smart hospital matching system tailored to Ethiopia’s healthcare challenges. The document covers the full project lifecycle from feasibility analysis, scope definition, time and cost estimation, resource staffing, change control, risk management, through to system design, implementation, and evaluation.

Key achievements of the project include:

-	A hybrid software life cycle model (Prototyping + Incremental + Spiral‑inspired) that balances flexibility with risk control, fully aligned with the course curriculum.
-	A detailed Work Breakdown Structure (WBS) and network diagram with critical path calculation, demonstrating realistic 18‑week scheduling.
-	A cost estimate of $34,730 USD (approx. 5.46 million ETB) with 10% contingency, including exchange rate risk mitigation.
-	A complete Risk Register (11 risks) with assigned owners and mitigation strategies.
-	A functional prototype with five core screens (login, symptom input, results, details, offline mode) built with Flutter and Node.js.
-	Testing and evaluation showing 100% pass rate of core test cases, 87% matching accuracy, and UAT satisfaction of 4.2/5.

The system meets all identified success criteria: patient input under 2 minutes, matching accuracy ≥85%, offline sync ≥95%, and compliance with Ethiopian data protection laws. The project closure criteria are clearly defined, and the system is ready for pilot deployment in Addis Ababa.

7.2 Recommendations

Based on the project’s findings, the following recommendations are made for future iterations and broader deployment:

1. Performance optimization – Address the remaining medium‑severity issue (response time under heavy load >100 concurrent users) by implementing caching and database indexing before nationwide scaling.

2. User interface refinement – Incorporate UAT feedback to simplify symptom input using chip‑based selection and add a dark mode.

3. Multi‑language support – Expand the interface to include Amharic, Afaan Oromo, and other local languages to increase rural accessibility.

4. Integration with national health systems – Pursue Ministry of Health approval to integrate CareConnect with Ethiopia’s digital health strategy, enabling real‑time hospital data feeds.

5. Sustainability plan – Secure funding from NGOs or government sponsors to cover hosting, maintenance, and helpdesk support beyond the pilot phase.

6. Future feature additions – Consider telemedicine consultation, appointment booking with payment, and AI‑based symptom checker in phase 2.

By following these recommendations, CareConnect can evolve into a scalable, sustainable, and impactful digital health platform for all Ethiopians.

